    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/card/task_001/scope_drift",
      "@type": "asbval:ScopeDriftAssertion",
      "asbval:drift_notes": [
        "The candidate card focuses on model instantiation, forward pass validation, and logging procedures, which are implementation/testing concerns. The paper's scope is broader: it presents IDSL_MINT as a complete framework for training and deploying custom models on MS/MS spectra, with emphasis on training data curation, model accuracy evaluation, and application to annotation tasks.",
        "The card's expected outputs are narrowly technical (PyTorch model instance, tensor shapes, execution logs), whereas the paper's actual outputs are scientific (fingerprint predictions, annotation improvements, Tanimoto similarity scores, lipid class accuracies).",
        "The card does not mention key IDSL_MINT-specific inputs/outputs: .msp file format, .yaml configuration files, fingerprint descriptors (ECFP, MACCS Keys), or Tanimoto similarity matching\u2014all central to the paper's contribution."
      ],
      "asbval:n_drift_notes": 3,
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "task_001",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "card",
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:56:32.857434+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/attention-mechanism-validation/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "IDSL_MINT was developed upon the transformer model architecture originally proposed by Vaswani et al. [17] and is implemented within the python PyTorch framework... The embedded m/z space is converted into the encoder structure of the transformer model... We used a sinusoidal positional encoding similar to Vaswani et al. [17] to account for the effects of intensity on the tokenized embedded m/z tokens",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes transformer encoder with positional encoding and multi-head attention applied to MS/MS spectra, but does not explicitly discuss validation of numerical stability or attention mechanism correctness as a standalone task. The paper implements these components but does not present a validation workflow as the card describes.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1186-s13321-024-00804-5",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "partial",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "attention-mechanism-validation",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Validates that a transformer-based encoder with multi-head self-attention and positional encoding processes mass spectrometry input tensors correctly without numerical instability.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000361"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T13:57:20.343969+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000339"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/attention-mechanism-validation/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "IDSL_MINT was developed using Python 3.10 and implemented with PyTorch 2.0... The model weights are exported at the directory outlined in the configuration file (.yaml), for the minimal LOSS value achieved during the training phase.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes IDSL_MINT training and inference workflow but does not explicitly describe a validation step for the attention mechanism before training. The scope assumes a validation task that is not explicitly documented in the paper.",
